[3] Liberia: Christmas celebration
Date: 24 Dec 2014
Source: National public radio [edited]
http://www.npr.org/blogs/goatsandsoda/2014/12/24/372669481/christmas-in-liberia-ebola-fears-no-snow-holiday-spirit


Christmas is celebrated in Liberia by painting houses decoratively and carols playing on the radio. It is a festive time of year. Commentator Siatta Scott Johnson says there's a government order to paint all office buildings, shops and private houses by mid-December 2014, otherwise you face a fine. She says Ebola has not changed that practice. The past couple of months have seen the number of new cases declining and stabilizing in Liberia.

Ebola specialists warn that creeping complacency is the new enemy and that Liberians must remain vigilant. A presidential order is in force, banning large gatherings in the capital city Monrovia to keep people from crowding together and possibly spreading the virus, including on beaches. (And neighboring Guinea and Sierra Leone have banned public celebrations altogether during the festive season because of Ebola.)...

