[9] Cote d'Ivoire girds its loins
Date: 24 Dec 2014
From: Dr Adjogoua, Edgard Valery <edgardadjogoua@pasteur.ci> [edited]


Cote d'Ivoire shares on all its western part, a common border with Guinea and Liberia, major epidemic Cote d'Ivoire countries of the Ebola virus disease. The north western part of Cote d'Ivoire is bordered by Mali, a new infected country. This reality makes it the country most at risk in West Africa, but so far, no cases have been reported and confirmed.

The country is preparing to face a possible epidemic. In order to face this situation, a national committee to fight against Ebola virus has been introduced. The National Institute of Public Hygiene coordinates and monitors the activities in collaboration with the Institut Pasteur of Cote d'Ivoire (IPCI), which is responsible for the laboratory diagnosis of any suspected cases. These 2 Institutes ensure, firstly, the training of health workers about precautions to take to protect themselves from infection with Ebola virus, and secondly, awareness. In response to this epidemic risk, what has been done at the laboratory level?

A situation analysis was used to verify the diagnostic capabilities of the Institute, the capacity and level of containment and biosafety, human resources and infrastructure. Indeed, IPCI has a security level 3 laboratory obtained as part of a US President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) TB project and a biological resource bank for the secure storage of samples.

The presence of an experienced team enabled biosafety risk assessment and the provision of quality procedures and biosafety. This team has enabled the provision of more appropriate personal protective equipment. A needs assessment of consumables and small equipment was made.

One of the major strengths has been the availability of human resources. The Pasteur team is composed of virologists, epidemiologists, veterinarians, pharmacists, engineers, technicians, inventory manager, logistics etc. At the infrastructure level, an inventory of the different laboratories was done. The Department of Epidemic Virus and platform for molecular biology of the IPCI have the equipment to perform diagnostic tests in real-time and conventional PCR.

As technical staff was insufficiently prepared for this epidemic risk, training was organized and upgrading sessions at national and international level. A biologist from the IPCI was trained by WHO in the Uganda Virus Research Institute (UVRI) on molecular diagnosis of filoviruses [The UVRI has experts from the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) among its staff. - Mod.JW]. A sample management system from the peripheral level (health center) to the laboratory at the IPCI has been defined. Each district of the western border of the country was given a triple packaging container approved for the transport of highly pathogenic microorganisms.

The primers, probes and positive controls were provided initially by the regional laboratory for arboviruses and hemorrhagic viral fevers in Dakar [Senegal] and then by WHO. In the field, 6 regional laboratories developed through collaboration with CDC were trained for Ebola activities. The IPCI set up in each laboratory involved in the response a team responsible for the collection and the transport of samples to Abidjan [the capital]; to provide a list of equipment and training necessary for biosafety; provide technical procedures for the collection, storage and transport of samples; and supervise the activities of regional labs. IPCI also makes the diagnosis of suspected samples and maintains a comprehensive database of the samples received and finally ensures and coordinates the proper disposal of laboratory waste as part of the response to the epidemic. 63 samples of suspected Ebola cases were collected from March to December 2014 in Cote d'Ivoire. Only 9 samples were taken from people who had stayed in the epidemic area. All these 63 samples tested by real-time PCR with Altona Kit (Realstar filovirus screen RT-PCR kit 1.0) after extraction with mini-Qiagen kit were negative for Ebola and Marburg viruses. Among these samples, 2 were positive for the yellow fever serology (IgM).

--
Dr Adjogoua, Edgard Valery
Institut Pasteur of Cote d'Ivoire
<edgardadjogoua@pasteur.ci>

[ProMED welcomes firsthand reports from the field like this. - Mod.JW]

